import os
import time
import requests
from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys

# Define 10 cat breeds
cat_breeds = [
    'Persian Cat', 'Siamese Cat', 'Maine Coon Cat', 'Bengal Cat', 'Ragdoll Cat',
    'British Shorthair', 'Sphynx Cat', 'Abyssinian Cat', 'Russian Blue', 'Scottish Fold'
]

# Set target images per breed
images_per_breed = 330
base_dir = 'cat_images'

# Set up Selenium
driver = webdriver.Chrome()

for breed in cat_breeds:
    query = breed + " cat"
    folder_name = breed.lower().replace(" ", "_")
    save_path = os.path.join(base_dir, folder_name)
    os.makedirs(save_path, exist_ok=True)

    print(f"Searching: {query}")
    driver.get("https://www.bing.com/images")
    time.sleep(1)

    search_box = driver.find_element(By.NAME, "q")
    search_box.clear()
    search_box.send_keys(query)
    search_box.send_keys(Keys.RETURN)
    time.sleep(2)

    # Scroll to load images
    for _ in range(5):
        driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight);")
        time.sleep(1)

    images = driver.find_elements(By.CSS_SELECTOR, "img.mimg")
    print(f"Found {len(images)} images for {breed}")

    count = 0
    for idx, img in enumerate(images):
        try:
            src = img.get_attribute("src")
            if not src or "http" not in src:
                continue

            img_data = requests.get(src).content
            ext = src.split(".")[-1].split("?")[0]
            if ext.lower() not in ["jpg", "jpeg", "png"]:
                ext = "jpg"

            file_path = os.path.join(save_path, f"{folder_name}_{idx}.{ext}")
            with open(file_path, "wb") as f:
                f.write(img_data)
            count += 1

            if count >= images_per_breed:
                break
        except Exception as e:
            print("Error downloading image:", e)

    print(f"Downloaded {count} images for {breed}\n")

driver.quit()

import os
import time
import requests
from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys

# Set up constants
cat_breeds = [
    'Persian Cat', 'Siamese Cat', 'Maine Coon Cat', 'Bengal Cat', 'Ragdoll Cat',
    'British Shorthair', 'Sphynx Cat', 'Abyssinian Cat', 'Russian Blue', 'Scottish Fold'
]
images_per_breed = 330
base_dir = 'cat_images'

# Set up Selenium
driver = webdriver.Chrome()

for breed in cat_breeds:
    query = breed + " cat"
    folder_name = breed.lower().replace(" ", "_")
    save_path = os.path.join(base_dir, folder_name)
    os.makedirs(save_path, exist_ok=True)

    # Check existing images
    existing_images = [f for f in os.listdir(save_path) if f.lower().endswith(('.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png'))]
    already_downloaded = len(existing_images)
    remaining = images_per_breed - already_downloaded

    if remaining <= 0:
        print(f"✅ {folder_name} already has {already_downloaded} images. Skipping...")
        continue

    print(f"\n🔍 Searching: {query} | Already: {already_downloaded} | Need: {remaining}")
    driver.get("https://www.bing.com/images")
    time.sleep(1)

    search_box = driver.find_element(By.NAME, "q")
    search_box.clear()
    search_box.send_keys(query)
    search_box.send_keys(Keys.RETURN)
    time.sleep(2)

    # Scroll more times to load additional images
    for _ in range(10):
        driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight);")
        time.sleep(1)

    images = driver.find_elements(By.CSS_SELECTOR, "img.mimg")
    print(f"🖼 Found {len(images)} images for {breed}")

    count = 0
    start_index = already_downloaded

    for idx, img in enumerate(images):
        if count >= remaining:
            break
        try:
            src = img.get_attribute("src")
            if not src or "http" not in src:
                continue

            img_data = requests.get(src, timeout=10).content
            ext = src.split(".")[-1].split("?")[0].lower()
            if ext not in ["jpg", "jpeg", "png"]:
                ext = "jpg"

            file_path = os.path.join(save_path, f"{folder_name}_{start_index + count}.{ext}")
            with open(file_path, "wb") as f:
                f.write(img_data)

            count += 1
        except Exception as e:
            print("❌ Error downloading image:", e)

    print(f"✅ Downloaded {count} new images for {breed} | Total: {already_downloaded + count}")

driver.quit()

import os
import time
import requests
import hashlib
from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys

# Set up constants
cat_breeds = [
    'Persian Cat', 'Siamese Cat', 'Maine Coon Cat', 'Bengal Cat', 'Ragdoll Cat',
    'British Shorthair', 'Sphynx Cat', 'Abyssinian Cat', 'Russian Blue', 'Scottish Fold'
]
images_per_breed = 330
base_dir = 'cat_images'

# Set up Selenium
driver = webdriver.Chrome()

for breed in cat_breeds:
    query = breed + " cat"
    folder_name = breed.lower().replace(" ", "_")
    save_path = os.path.join(base_dir, folder_name)
    os.makedirs(save_path, exist_ok=True)

    # Check existing images
    existing_images = [f for f in os.listdir(save_path) if f.lower().endswith(('.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png'))]
    already_downloaded = len(existing_images)
    remaining = images_per_breed - already_downloaded

    if remaining <= 0:
        print(f"✅ {folder_name} already has {already_downloaded} images. Skipping...")
        continue

    print(f"\n🔍 Searching: {query} | Already: {already_downloaded} | Need: {remaining}")
    driver.get("https://www.bing.com/images")
    time.sleep(1)

    search_box = driver.find_element(By.NAME, "q")
    search_box.clear()
    search_box.send_keys(query)
    search_box.send_keys(Keys.RETURN)
    time.sleep(2)

    # Scroll more times to load additional images
    for _ in range(10):
        driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight);")
        time.sleep(1)

    images = driver.find_elements(By.CSS_SELECTOR, "img.mimg")
    print(f"🖼 Found {len(images)} images for {breed}")

    # Build hash set of existing images
    hash_set = set()
    for file in existing_images:
        try:
            with open(os.path.join(save_path, file), 'rb') as f:
                file_hash = hashlib.md5(f.read()).hexdigest()
                hash_set.add(file_hash)
        except:
            continue

    count = 0
    start_index = already_downloaded

    for idx, img in enumerate(images):
        if count >= remaining:
            break
        try:
            src = img.get_attribute("src")
            if not src or "http" not in src:
                continue

            img_data = requests.get(src, timeout=10).content
            img_hash = hashlib.md5(img_data).hexdigest()

            if img_hash in hash_set:
                continue  # skip duplicates

            ext = src.split(".")[-1].split("?")[0].lower()
            if ext not in ["jpg", "jpeg", "png"]:
                ext = "jpg"

            file_path = os.path.join(save_path, f"{folder_name}_{start_index + count}.{ext}")
            with open(file_path, "wb") as f:
                f.write(img_data)

            hash_set.add(img_hash)
            count += 1
        except Exception as e:
            print("❌ Error downloading image:", e)

    print(f"✅ Downloaded {count} new images for {breed} | Total: {already_downloaded + count}")

driver.quit()

import os
import shutil
import random
from pathlib import Path

# ✅ Updated paths
original_dataset_dir = r'C:\Users\ariff\Desktop\ProjectAI\cat_images'
output_base_dir = r'C:\Users\ariff\Desktop\ProjectAI\cat_images'

# Split ratios
train_ratio = 0.7
val_ratio = 0.15
test_ratio = 0.15

# Target folders
splits = ['train', 'val', 'test']

for category in os.listdir(original_dataset_dir):
    category_path = os.path.join(original_dataset_dir, category)
    if not os.path.isdir(category_path):
        continue

    # Skip already split folders
    if category.lower() in splits:
        continue

    # List all image files
    images = [img for img in os.listdir(category_path) if img.lower().endswith(('.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png'))]
    random.shuffle(images)

    total = len(images)
    train_end = int(train_ratio * total)
    val_end = train_end + int(val_ratio * total)

    # Divide into splits
    split_images = {
        'train': images[:train_end],
        'val': images[train_end:val_end],
        'test': images[val_end:]
    }

    for split in splits:
        split_dir = os.path.join(output_base_dir, split, category)
        os.makedirs(split_dir, exist_ok=True)

        for img_name in split_images[split]:
            src = os.path.join(category_path, img_name)
            dst = os.path.join(split_dir, img_name)
            shutil.copy2(src, dst)

print("✅ Dataset successfully split into train/val/test.")

✅ Dataset successfully split into train/val/test.

#Model Builder
def build_model(base_model_class, input_shape=(160, 160, 3), num_classes=11, freeze_base=True):
    base_model = base_model_class(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=input_shape)
    
    if freeze_base:
        for layer in base_model.layers:
            layer.trainable = False  
    
    x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(base_model.output)
    output = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')(x)
    model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)
    
    return model
In [9]:
def train_and_evaluate(model, train_gen, val_gen, test_gen, epochs=50):
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    start_time = time.time()
    history = model.fit(train_gen, validation_data=val_gen, epochs=epochs)
    training_time = time.time() - start_time
    
    return history, training_time

In [25]:
def plot_loss(history, model_name="Model"):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Train Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Val Loss')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

In [27]:

In [28]:

Justification On Low Accuracy

DenseNet121 performed better than ResNet50 and MobileNetV3 mainly because of how its architecture is built. DenseNet connects each layer to every other layer, which helps it reuse features and pass gradients more efficiently during training. This means it learns better and faster, even when the input data isn't heavily preprocessed. On the other hand, ResNet50, although it uses shortcut connections, doesn't have the same level of feature reuse, which might explain why it had higher training and validation loss. MobileNetV3 is designed to be lightweight for mobile devices, so it's faster but not as powerful when it comes to handling complex image details like distinguishing between similar-looking cat breeds.

Since all three models were trained with just simple rescaling and no advanced augmentation, the fact that DenseNet still performed so well shows it’s really good at learning from limited or less varied data.

y_true = test_generator.classes
num_classes = test_generator.num_classes
y_true_oh = to_categorical(y_true, num_classes=num_classes)

# Store all models
models = {
    "ResNet50": model_resnet,
    "DenseNet121": model_densenet,
    "MobileNetV3": model_mobile
}

# Evaluate all
results = {}

for name, model in models.items():
    print(f"Evaluating {name}...")
    
    y_pred_probs = model.predict(test_generator)
    y_pred_labels = np.argmax(y_pred_probs, axis=1)
    
    acc = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred_labels)
    mAP = average_precision_score(y_true_oh, y_pred_probs, average='macro')
    
    results[name] = {
        "Accuracy": acc,
        "mAP": mAP
    }
    
    print(f"{name} - Accuracy: {acc:.4f}, mAP: {mAP:.4f}")

# Show results
print("\nModel Comparison:")
print(f"{'Model':<15} {'Accuracy':<10} {'mAP':<10}")
for name, metrics in results.items():
    print(f"{name:<15} {metrics['Accuracy']:<10.4f} {metrics['mAP']:<10.4f}")

from tensorflow.keras.models import load_model
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load DenseNet121 model
model_densenet = load_model("model_densenet121.h5")

# True labels and class names
y_true = test_generator.classes
class_names = list(test_generator.class_indices.keys())

# Predict
y_pred_densenet = model_densenet.predict(test_generator)
y_pred_densenet = np.argmax(y_pred_densenet, axis=1)

# Plot confusion matrix
ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(
    y_true, y_pred_densenet, display_labels=class_names, xticks_rotation=45
)
plt.title("DenseNet121 Confusion Matrix")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, ConfusionMatrixDisplay
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Step 1: Predict on the full test set
y_true = test_generator.classes  

# Predict for each model
y_pred_resnet = np.argmax(model_resnet.predict(test_generator, verbose=1), axis=1)
y_pred_mobile = np.argmax(model_mobile.predict(test_generator, verbose=1), axis=1)
y_pred_densenet = np.argmax(model_densenet.predict(test_generator, verbose=1), axis=1)

# Step 2: Compute accuracies
acc_resnet = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred_resnet)
acc_mobile = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred_mobile)
acc_dense = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred_densenet)

# Step 3: Build results table
results = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['ResNet50', 'MobileNetV3', 'DenseNet121'],
    'Accuracy': [acc_resnet, acc_mobile, acc_dense],
    'Training Time (s)': [training_time_resnet, training_time_mobile, training_time_densenet]
})

# Step 4: Display results
from IPython.display import display
display(results)

# Step 5: Plot accuracy
plt.bar(results['Model'], results['Accuracy'], color=['red', 'blue', 'green'])
plt.title("Model Accuracy Comparison")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.grid(axis='y')
plt.show()

# Step 6: Plot training time
plt.bar(results['Model'], results['Training Time (s)'], color=['red', 'blue', 'green'])
plt.title("Model Training Time Comparison")
plt.ylabel("Time (seconds)")
plt.grid(axis='y')
plt.show()
